  "description": {
    "en": "Learn multiprocessing — Process, Pool, shared memory, and how to bypass the GIL for CPU-bound tasks using separate processes.",
    "ta": "multiprocessing கற்றுக்கொள்ளுங்கள் — Process, Pool, shared memory, CPU-bound tasks-க்கு GIL-ஐ கடக்க தனி processes பயன்படுத்துதல்."
  },
  "xp_reward": 75,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Separate Kitchens\n\nVaathiyaar opens multiple kitchens. \"With threading, all workers share ONE kitchen and take turns with the stove (GIL). With **multiprocessing**, each worker gets their OWN kitchen — true parallel cooking!\"\n\n### Threading vs Multiprocessing\n\n| Feature | Threading | Multiprocessing |\n|---------|----------|------------------|\n| Memory | Shared | Separate per process |\n| GIL | Limited by GIL | No GIL restriction |\n| Best for | I/O-bound | CPU-bound |\n| Overhead | Low | Higher (process creation) |\n| Communication | Easy (shared vars) | Harder (serialization) |\n\n### Key Classes\n\n```python\nfrom multiprocessing import Process, Pool\n\n# Process: manual control\np = Process(target=func, args=(arg,))\np.start()\np.join()\n\n# Pool: managed workers\nwith Pool(4) as pool:\n    results = pool.map(func, data)\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** Multiprocessing creates SEPARATE Python interpreters. Each has its own GIL, so they truly run in parallel on different CPU cores. The trade-off is higher memory usage and slower communication."
  },
